Stakeholders have said reopening of Lekki Toll Gate on April 1 will help the government to recover losses suffered in #ENDSARS protest. They faulted those plotting protests against the reopening, urging them to suspend such action. Official of the firm handling the facility said it understood sentiments that greeted the protest, its implications to Lagos and had sacrificed a lot during the 18-month closure. He noted that the company said it owed local and foreign lenders billions of naira, in addition to hundreds of jobless workers since the closure.   Court to hear ex-Army Chief’s suit against EFCC June 8     Defection: Court fixes April 11 for judgment in suit seeking…     China plane crash: One of two black boxes found   Speaking on a television programme, Lagos State Commissioner for Information and Strategy Gbenga Omotoso said LCC owes local lenders about N11.6 billion and foreign lenders $31.1 million. A Lagos-based economist, Diran Thompson, said while the state struggled to rebuild the economy battered by the protest, any uprising would be counterproductive as it could derail the ambitious 4th Mainland Bridge dream. He noted that the other PPP investors would be discouraged by the action. Another source close to the company said despite suspension of tolling operations, the Security Department, comprising Personnel and Dedicated Agencies–Man O’ War, Police and Lagos Traffic Management Authority (LASTMA), did not relent in providing safety and security services to the company, he public and its host communities.